SIMPLE: pome
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Pome
<hw>Pome</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>pomum</ets> a
fruit: cf. F. <ets>pomme</ets> apple. Cf. <er>Pomade</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A fruit composed of several
cartilaginous or bony carpels inclosed in an adherent fleshy mass, which
is partly receptacle and partly calyx, as an apple, quince, or
pear.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(R. C. Ch.)</fld> <def>A ball of silver or other
metal, which is filled with hot water, and used by the priest in cold
weather to warm his hands during the service.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pome</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Pome
<hw>Pome</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>pommer</ets>. See
<er>Pome</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <def>To grow to a head, or form a
head in growing.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pomegranate</ent>⟦br⟧
